name: Ragnar Trail Buckeye Country - OH
intro:
Ragnar Trail Buckeye Country-OH will not be held in 2017. We're dedicated to curating the best trail relay experience we can offer the Buckeye State, so stay tuned! Sign up for the waitlist here for immediate updates about when this race will be available again! 
 
Questions? Comments? Contact customer service at customerservice@ragnarrelay.com.
 
Ragnar Trail Buckeye Country-OH presented by Salomon is an adventure that will leave your heart happy. Teams of 8 (or 4) will run relay-style in late September to conquer a set of single track trails that start and finish at Ragnar Village over two days and one night. Situated in Central Ohio at Dillion State Park, about 15 minutes outside of Zanesville, this venue features fun, fast, flowing running trails that carve through lush hardwood forests and over babbling streams. Runners will set up camp on plush grass near a gorgeous lake surrounded by white sandy beaches. When the sun goes down, the runners (and the party) don't stop. A billion stars overhead, bonfires, movies, s'mores and new friends come together to create an unforgettable weekend.

Ragnar Trail Buckeye Country-OH presented by Salomon is an adventure that will leave your heart happy. Situated in Central Ohio at Dillion State Park, about 15 minutes outside of Zanesville, this venue features fun, fast, flowing running trails that carve through lush hardwood forests and over babbling streams. Runners will set up camp on plush grass near a gorgeous lake surrounded by white sandy beaches. When the sun goes down, the runners (and the party) don’t stop. A billion stars overhead, bonfires, movies, s’mores and new friends come together to create an unforgettable weekend. Mark your calendar for Sept. 30-Oct. 1, and learn what it means to find you #innerWILD!

Ragnar has partnered with AOA for the Ohio race. AOA (Appalachia Outdoor Adventure) is a non-profit organization whose mission is to support, develop, and participate in physically demanding outdoor activities. They are dedicated to designing, building, and maintaining trails in the Central Ohio area. We are extremely happy to support such a great organization, not to mention they build some darn good trails! If you want to find out more about AOA and how you can support their efforts, check them out HERE.
village:
Ragnar Village is the heart and soul of the event. Each trail begins and ends in Ragnar Village. It is the start line, the finish line, and the exchange point. After each loop you will return to the support of your teammates and the adulation of the teams around you. Ragnar Village will be complete with:

  • Bonfire
  • S'mores
  • Music
  • Food & snacks (Friday night pasta dinner included for each runner)
  • Billions of stars

The Ragnar Village will be located at Dillon State Park. Camping on plush grass? Check!

For more information on your team's campsite, see the Travel & Lodging page

Training by Salomon

At Salomon our goal is to inspire runners to go beyond the pavement and enjoy greater freedom to run anywhere. We believe that with some tips and training almost anyone can become a trail runner and run the Ragnar Trail Relay. We are here to guide you on your training journey as you prepare to run the Ragnar Trail Relay.

results:
RAGNAR TRAIL BUCKEYE COUNTRY-OH FINAL RESULTS AND AWARDS

Congratulations to all the teams that managed to finish this tough course through the night and sun and rain!  We are in awe of all of you. Final Results for Ragnar Trail Buckeye Country – OH 2016 are now posted and can be found here: Buckeye Country-OH 2016 Results.

If your team finished 1st,2nd or 3rd in your respective team category, we have an award to send to commemorate your accomplishment.  There is an award for all team members that will be mailed to your Team Captain. 

Team Captains, please be sure that your current mailing address is accurate on your Ragnar Profile.  We cannot mail to PO Boxes so please be sure you have entered a physical address.

And now for the awards you have all been waiting for. 

Best Team Costume:

Team #79 – They Got Us Workin’ In Shifts (The Big Lebowski – reference)

Best Team Campsite:

Team #35 – Ragnar Trail Rookies

Best Team Spirit:

Team #49 – Out Chasing Booty 

And, in the category of Best Team Name:

Team #59 – Trail-er Park Girls  

Again, if you are a Category Award Winner please be sure that your current mailing address is accurate on your Ragnar Profile.

meta_description: Ragnar Trail Buckeye Country-OH presented by Salomon is an adventure that will leave your heart happy. Teams of 8 (or 4) will run relay-style in late September to conquer a set of single track trails that start and finish at Ragnar Village over two days and one night. Situated in Central Ohio at Dillion State Park, about 15 minutes outside of Zanesville, this venue features fun, fast, flowing running trails that carve through lush hardwood forests and over babbling streams.

legs.name: Green Loop
legs.description: The Green Loop leaves the Village with both other Loops, running past a broad white sand beach before climbing up away from the lake and turning left from the Yellow and Red Loops. From here the Green Loop continues on a mellow cinder trail for another ¼ mile before swinging left again on a single-track through the woods, primarily used by Dillon’s equestrian riders. Near mile 1.5 the trail pops out of the trees and crosses the main park road for another single-track. This section weaves through a large open meadow for a while before plunging back into the canopy where the trail gets gnarly, twisting and turning on a technical rooty surface. At mile 2.5 the trail crosses the outbound Yellow and Red Loops. This is your marker to put on your kick. Less than a mile to go and all downhill back to the Village, and that white sand beach.

legs.name: Yellow Loop
legs.description: Just like the other two loops, the Yellow leaves the Transition Tent and skirts the outside of the Village, with Dillon Lake on the left. After the Green Loop peels off, the Yellow and Red continue together for another ½ mile before splitting themselves, Red going left and Yellow turning right. The next mile and a half are fast smooth sections of hiking trails through the trees. Mile 2.5 is the turning point for the Yellow Loop. From here, the trail swoops and dips for 2 miles, in and out of creek drainages as it makes its way back home, views of the lake breaking through the trees. If your road shoes could see the look on your face, they’d be pretty jealous. The last half miles joins the Red and then Green Loops and then it is all over. You cross under the arch and find yourself next to the bonfire. We won’t tell your road shoes if you don’t either.

legs.name: Red Loop
legs.description: This Loop is most excellent. Nearly all fun and fast with some sections of technical thrown in to keep you on your toes. After splitting from Yellow at mile 1, the loop stays high, winding its way through trees and rocks, and past a cemetery nearly 200 years old. Sweet! Mile 3 is the turning point that drops the trail down near the lake. For the next three miles you get a front row seat to awesome. This section will make you feel like Daniel Day-Lewis running through the forest, hatchet in hand. Well, actually don’t run with a hatchet, but the long dark pony tail would be nice, or a loin cloth. Either way the moonlight shimmering off the lake, that’s what it’s all about.

travel.content:
TRAVEL & LODGING

Directions

Directions to Dillon State Park are found here

Camping

Each team will pick a location to set up their team campsite in the Ragnar Village. Camping will be located in an awesome beachy area on an small peninsula protruding into Dillon Lake. Don't worry--there will be plenty of cushy grass on which to place your temporary home during the weekend. Awards will be given for the best decorated team campsite and almost anything goes: tents, canopies, couches, camping chairs, BBQ's, kiddie pools full of Kool-Aid, whatever. Note that the venue opens to participants on Thursday afternoon, after 4:00 p.m. 

SUSTAINABILITY

Ragnar seeks ways to reduce the carbon footprint of our races. We ask you join us in this effort by carpooling on your drive to the race and striving to bring only two (2) vehicles per team.
